[1
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 09:18:28 -0500
From: Alix Fano <afano@MA.NEAVS.COM>

Regarding Henry Wilde's (Nov. 22) post about the fact that there are
thousands of people walking around with pig valves: A recent article in New
Scientist (I believe August 8, 1998) confirmed that pig valves (which are
indeed taken from slaughterhouses, MHJ [Thank you!) are treated with
glutaraldehyde (to kill their antigenicity), making pig heart valves as
"dead as toenails" according to the New Scientist article. So pig heart
valves cannot be compared to whole, live pig organs which carry a much
larger reservoir of viruses. It should also be noted that homograft valves
(derived from human cadavers) function comparably to pig valves. And new
synthetic valves preclude the use of the pig valves. They also last longer.
With regards to Richard Kennerly's question about TSE of swine: this was
raised as a concern for xenografted organs in a report by Peter Laing of
Salomon Brothers, London for Sandoz entitled, "The Unrecognized Potential
of Xenotransplantation" (January 1996).
With respect to whether pigs can be bred to be pathogen-free: In a 1996
report, the U.S. Institute of Medicine acknowledged that it is impossible
to rear completely pathogen-free animals, because endogenous retroviruses
can be passed transplacentally from mother to offspring. In addition, the
genes for porcine endogenous retroviruses (PERVs), of which there are
several different types, are scattered throughout the pig genome, and are
shed by pigs' kidneys, lungs, hearts, livers, aortas, and skin - all organs
being considered for transplants. Numerous scientists, including the
discoverers of these PERVs, have warned that placing live pig organs in
humans is akin to injecting patients with live viruses.
Who will take responsibility for the outbreak of a new epidemic?
--
Alix Fano
e-mail: afano@ma.neavs.com
