[2
Date: Wed, 25 Nov 1998 11:13:48 +1000
From: Peter Collignon <peter_collignon@dpa.act.gov.au>

Pig valves are extensively treated before they are implanted usually with
glutaraldehydes and/or other stabilising substances. They are therefore not
expected to have live cells (and presumably any live viruses) when they are
implanted into a person. The only infective agents that could presumably
survive the processing of the valves might be prions. I have however seen
no data on whether dementia was more common in pig valve recipients. Even
if dementia was more common it would be very difficult to interpret this
data because pig valves (rather than artificial valves) are often used in
older patients and those with an expected shorter life expectancy because
they are thought to wear out faster.
There relevance to the xenograft debate is however likely to not be of much
benefit. As they are effectively sterilised chemically before they are put
into a person this is obviously a very different situation to placing
billions of live cells and their associated viruses (e.g. in a liver) into
a heavily immunosuppressed person.
--
A/Prof Peter Collignon
Infectious Diseases physician and microbiologist
The Canberra Hospital
Australia
e-mail: peter_collignon@dpa.act.gov.au
