[3
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 11:29:43 -0500
From: Richard Chong <rchong@GlobalStrat.com>

>>... should a recipient, who is 'carrying' a foreign organ be afraid of
microorganisms, which are pathogenic to the donating animal?<<
An example which may contribute food for thought to this thread is the
recent outbreak of Influenza A (H5N1) which occurred in Hong Kong. You may
recall that several people fell ill and some died after seemingly
contracting a virus from chickens. Earlier this month more details came to
light. Dr Mak Kwok-hang, Consultant (Community Medicine) to the Hong Kong
Department of Health reported that the primary mode of transmission of H5N1
infection is believed to be from poultry to man; most likely through
contact with the faeces of poultry. There is no evidence that H5N1
infection is transmitted to man from raw, chilled or frozen poultry foods.
Furthermore, evidences indicated that transmission of the virus from
person-to-person had occurred but was uncommon.
(Reference: ProMED Digest, Monday, 16 November 1998, Volume 98 : Number 290)
If memory serves correctly however, one theory indicated that the original
pool of the virus may have been in swine. In China, it is common to find
both swine and poultry in close quarters. It is possible that a swine virus
made its way to poultry which was exported to Hong Kong resulting in the
subsequent H5N1 outbreak.
In this particular case, one must consider the possibility that the "middle
layer" (poultry) might not be necessary to promote the spread of virus if
the human host already had suitable receptors. Furthermore, would a direct
link to a human host promote faster mutation of the virus to allow more
efficient person-to-person transmission?
--
